# Fluff Date: 2026-02-20 17:30:00
overview:<p>The Targe was introduced in 3081 by Cosara Weaponries on Northwind, designed to fill a reconnaissance and cavalry role within the fledgling Republic Armed Forces. Named after the round shield carried by the Scottish Highlanders of ancient Terra, the forty-ton medium BattleMech was born from Cosara's ambition to move beyond their reputation for solid but unremarkable designs like the Crab and Black Watch. An extensive analysis of RAF needs produced strict guidelines calling for a medium 'Mech capable of exceeding 160 kph in short bursts with a missile-based primary armament supported by lasers.</p><p>The resulting design was hamstrung by compromises between speed, protection, and firepower, earning the Targe a lackluster reputation that limited sales largely to the Northwind Highlanders. Cosara would produce a few hundred units before reassigning its assembly lines to civilian production, though development of improved variants continued across the Republic era.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Targe is built around a Pitban 320 Light fusion engine, providing a cruising speed of 86 kph and a top speed of 129 kph. When the MASC system is engaged, the 'Mech can briefly exceed 170 kph, making it one of the fastest medium designs in the Republic arsenal. Cosara selected the light engine over a more fragile extralight model to improve battlefield survivability, though this choice consumed nearly half the 'Mech's total tonnage. A small cockpit further saves weight at the expense of pilot comfort.</p><p>To maximize the limited weight remaining for protection, the design team selected Valiant Lamellor Special heavy ferro-fibrous armor, squeezing the most coverage possible from five tons of plating. Ten double heat sinks easily manage the modest heat output of the weapons array.</p><p>The armament reflects the compromises forced by the engine and MASC installation. A Shigunga MRM-10 launcher serves as the primary weapon, supplemented by three Diverse Optics extended-range small lasers. A single ton of missile ammunition provides adequate endurance for scouting engagements, protected by CASE in the event of a detonation. While underarmed for its weight class, the Targe relies on speed and hit-and-run tactics rather than sustained firepower exchanges.</p>

deployment:<p>Developed in 3109, nearly three decades after the original design, this variant represents Cosara's most significant revision to the Targe. The light fusion engine is replaced with an extralight model, a choice the original design team explicitly rejected due to survivability concerns. The freed tonnage supports an LRM-10 and three extended-range medium lasers, transforming the Targe from a short-range skirmisher into a more versatile support platform. With simplified weaponry and modernized internals, the design finally achieves the role of a reasonable fast support unit, though the fragility of the XL engine reintroduces the survivability trade-offs that shaped the original design philosophy.</p>

history:<p>The Targe's development began in the aftermath of the Jihad when Northwind joined the Republic of the Sphere. Cosara Weaponries, eager to supply the new state's military and rehabilitate its reputation after Northwind's occupation by the Word of Blake, conducted an extensive analysis of Republic Armed Forces needs. The resulting design specifications were ambitious, calling for a medium 'Mech with burst speeds exceeding 160 kph and missile-based armament, but the compromises required to meet those specifications produced a design that satisfied the letter of the requirements while falling short of expectations.</p><p>Production commenced in 3081, but sales proved disappointing from the outset. The RAF procurement office, while acknowledging the design met its stated requirements, found the Targe's limited firepower insufficient for front-line service. The Northwind Highlanders became the primary operators, purchasing the bulk of Cosara's output more from institutional loyalty to their homeworld manufacturer than tactical enthusiasm. The Targe was found most frequently in Highlander formations, generally assigned to scouting and counter-reconnaissance duties where its exceptional speed could be leveraged. Pilots developed a strafing tactic, approaching targets at high speed, firing at close range, and engaging MASC to escape before opponents could effectively return fire.</p><p>Cosara attempted to revitalize interest with the TRG-2N in 3084, addressing the most common complaints about the design's armament. While the upgraded variant performed well in simulations and dry runs, concerns about ammunition placement near the MASC system dampened enthusiasm among potential buyers. The Quartermaster's Office initiated an investigation into the safety issue, further stalling procurement.</p><p>By the early thirty-second century, the Targe had been largely relegated to second-line duties and garrison postings. The TRG-3M, introduced in 3109, represented a significant redesign that embraced the extralight engine Cosara had originally rejected. While a more capable platform overall, the Targe's poor reputation and the Bad Reputation quirk that followed the chassis continued to hamper sales across the remaining Republic era and into the ilClan period, leaving the design a footnote in Cosara's otherwise respectable catalog.</p>

